    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What makes a Sauvignon Blanc under $20 worth buying over cheaper options?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Quality Sauvignon Blancs under $20 typically come from established regions with ideal growing conditions, like New Zealand's Marlborough or France's Loire Valley, where the climate naturally preserves the grape's signature acidity and aromatics. These wines often feature more complex flavor profiles with distinct terroir characteristics - like the mineral backbone from Loire Valley's limestone soils or the intense tropical fruit notes from New Zealand's cool maritime climate. The extra investment usually means better winemaking techniques, including temperature-controlled fermentation and careful timing of harvest to capture optimal flavor compounds like methoxypyrazines that give Sauvignon Blanc its distinctive herbaceous character.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I choose New Zealand or French Sauvignon Blanc under $20?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">New Zealand Sauvignon Blancs under $20, particularly from Marlborough, offer bold tropical fruit flavors (passion fruit, grapefruit) with intense aromatics and bright acidity, making them perfect for those who enjoy vibrant, immediately appealing wines. French Sauvignon Blancs from Sancerre, Pouilly-Fumé, or Touraine in this price range tend to be more restrained and mineral-driven, with subtle gooseberry and citrus notes plus a distinctive flinty character from limestone soils. Choose New Zealand for fruit-forward dishes and casual drinking, or French for seafood, goat cheese, and when you want more food-pairing versatility.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can I keep an unopened Sauvignon Blanc under $20?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most Sauvignon Blancs under $20 are designed for immediate consumption and maintain their best quality for 1-3 years from vintage date when stored properly in a cool, dark place at 50-55°F. The wine's hallmark fresh acidity and vibrant aromatics begin to fade after this period, though higher-quality examples from regions like Sancerre may develop interesting honeyed notes and remain enjoyable for up to 5 years. Unlike age-worthy whites, these wines lose their defining characteristics - the bright grapefruit notes, grassy aromatics, and crisp finish - relatively quickly, so drink them while they showcase their youthful vibrancy.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What temperature should I serve Sauvignon Blanc to get the best value from my bottle?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve Sauvignon Blanc at 45-50°F (7-10°C) to maximize its aromatic intensity and balance - too cold and you'll mute the signature tropical fruit and herbaceous notes that justify the price point. This temperature allows the wine's volatile compounds like methoxypyrazines and terpenes to express themselves fully while maintaining the crisp acidity that makes Sauvignon Blanc so food-friendly. Achieve this by refrigerating for 2-3 hours or placing in an ice bucket for 15-20 minutes; overly chilled wine under $20 often tastes flat and loses the complexity you're paying for.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Sauvignon Blanc under $20 good for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sauvignon Blanc under $20 is excellent for beginners because it offers immediately recognizable flavors - bright citrus, tropical fruit, and fresh herbs - without requiring developed palate sophistication to appreciate. The wine's natural high acidity provides a clean, refreshing finish that's forgiving with food pairings, while the straightforward flavor profile helps newcomers identify specific tasting notes and build their palate vocabulary. Quality examples in this price range from reputable producers also demonstrate classic regional characteristics, giving beginners a solid foundation for understanding how terroir influences wine style.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the biggest mistakes people make when buying Sauvignon Blanc under $20?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is buying bottles that are too old - Sauvignon Blanc's appeal lies in its fresh, vibrant character, so avoid anything more than 2-3 years old unless it's from a premium Loire Valley producer. Another error is choosing based solely on alcohol content; many New World Sauvignon Blancs push 13.5-14% ABV, which can overpower the delicate aromatics and create a hot finish that diminishes food pairing versatility. Finally, many buyers overlook excellent value regions like Chile's Casablanca Valley or South Africa's Constantia, focusing only on famous names like Marlborough or Sancerre and missing exceptional wines at lower price points.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's a good alternative if I can't find quality Sauvignon Blanc under $20?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Albariño from Spain's Rías Baixas offers similar bright acidity and mineral-driven character with citrus and stone fruit notes, often providing exceptional value under $20. Grüner Veltliner from Austria delivers comparable herbaceous qualities with white pepper spice and citrus freshness, plus better food pairing versatility with richer dishes. For those who love New Zealand Sauvignon Blanc's tropical fruit intensity, consider Chilean examples from Casablanca Valley or South African versions from Constantia, which offer similar flavor profiles at often better price points due to favorable exchange rates and lower production costs.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Do I need to decant or let Sauvignon Blanc under $20 breathe before serving?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sauvignon Blanc under $20 typically doesn't require decanting and is best enjoyed immediately upon opening to capture its peak aromatics - the wine's volatile compounds that create those signature grapefruit, passion fruit, and grassy notes dissipate quickly when exposed to air. Unlike red wines or age-worthy whites, these wines are crafted for immediate accessibility and can actually lose their vibrant character if left open too long. However, if your bottle seems muted, a gentle swirl in the glass or 5-10 minutes of breathing can help, but extended aeration will diminish rather than enhance the wine's fresh, lively appeal.</p>
